03913nam a22006135i 9780691251356DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912513567 a10.1515/97806912513562doi  a(DE-B1597)666229  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBF789.C7bP3613 2018 7aART0150002bisacsh04a7001 aPastoureau, Michel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlue :bThe History of a Color /cMichel Pastoureau. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b100 color plates.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 AN UNCOMMON COLOR -- t2 A NEW COLOR -- t3 A MORAL COLOR -- t4 THE FAVORITE COLOR -- t5 BLUE TODAY -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tPhotography Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA beautifully illustrated visual and cultural history of the color blue throughout the agesBlue has had a long and topsy-turvy history in the Western world. The ancient Greeks scorned it as ugly and barbaric, but most Americans and Europeans now cite it as their favorite color. In this fascinating history, the renowned medievalist Michel Pastoureau traces the changing meanings of blue from its rare appearance in prehistoric art to its international ubiquity today. Any history of color is, above all, a social history. Pastoureau investigates how the ever-changing role of blue in society has been reflected in manuscripts, stained glass, heraldry, clothing, paintings, and popular culture. Beginning with the almost total absence of blue from ancient Western art and language, the story moves to medieval Europe. As people began to associate blue with the Virgin Mary, the color became a powerful element in church decoration and symbolism. Blue gained new favor as a royal color in the twelfth century and became a formidable political and military force during the French Revolution. As blue triumphed in the modern era, new shades were created and blue became the color of romance and the blues. Finally, Pastoureau follows blue into contemporary times, when military clothing gave way to the everyday uniform of blue jeans and blue became the universal and unifying color of the Earth as seen from space.Beautifully illustrated, Blue tells the intriguing story of our favorite color and the cultures that have hated it, loved it, and made it essential to some of our greatest works of art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlue in art. 0aBlue. 0aColorxPsychological aspectsxHistory. 0aColorxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aSymbolism of colorsxHistory. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691251356?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691251356423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691251356/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles